# Security and Secret Rules

## Hardcoded credentials — prohibited

Never generate or commit:

- Passwords, API secrets, signing secrets
- Firebase Admin keys or service-account JSON
- GitHub tokens, OAuth client secrets
- Private certificates, SSH keys, encryption keys
- Production deployment tokens

## Approved secret locations

- Google Secret Manager
- GitHub Actions Secrets
- Secure CI environment variables
- Local ignored environment files (`.env`, not committed)
- Approved password manager

## Client configuration

Flutter and Unity may contain non-secret public Firebase identifiers. They must **never** contain Firebase Admin credentials, privileged service credentials, or server signing secrets.

## Authorization

Authorization must occur on trusted systems (Cloud Functions, security rules). Never depend only on:

- Hidden button or disabled control
- Local role field
- Route guard alone
- Client-supplied institution ID

## Input validation

Validate all data crossing trust boundaries: Flutter↔Functions, Unity↔Flutter, Admin↔Functions, file uploads, Firestore writes, Storage uploads, seed input, CLI input.

## Least privilege

Do not use broad rules such as `allow read, write: if request.auth != null;` for production collections.

## Sensitive logging — never log

- Passwords, Firebase ID tokens, refresh tokens
- Private keys or full service-account JSON
- Sensitive student data
- Full authorization headers
- Private verification documents

## Environment isolation

- Development, Staging, Production are separate Firebase projects
- No silent default to production
- No cross-environment Storage URLs or Auth users

## Review checklist

- [ ] No secrets in diff
- [ ] Least privilege in rules and IAM
- [ ] Client trust boundaries respected
- [ ] Correct environment selected
